[3.8 Nested Subqueries]
    - subquery: select-from-where expression nested within another query.

    - common use: perform tests for 
        1) set membership
        2) make set comparisons
        3) determine set cardinality by nesting subqueries in the "where" clause.

    (3.8.1 Set Membership)
        - "in"
        - "not in"
            ex)
                SELECT DISTINCT name
                FROM instructor
                WHERE name NOT IN ('Mozart', 'Einstein');

            * "DISTINCT" used for removing duplicates.

    (3.8.2 Set Comparison)
        - "some" (greater than at least one)
            ex)
                SELECT name
                FROM instructor
                WHERE salary > SOME (SELECT salary
                                     FROM instructor
                                     WHERE dept_name = 'Bio');

            -> the subquery generates the set of all salary values for all instructors in the Bio department.

        - "all" (greater than all)
            ex)
                SELECT name
                FROM instructor
                WHERE salary > ALL (SELECT salary
                                    FROM instructor
                                    WHERE dpet_name = 'Bio');

        * BUT these are rare in modern SQL practice!!!
            -> "> SOME (subquery)" just use "> (SELECT MIN(...) FROM)"

            -> "> ALL (subquery)" just use "> (SELECT MAX(...) FROM"

            -> "= SOME" just use "IN"

            -> "<> ALL" just use "NOT IN"

    (3.8.3 Test for Empty Relations)
        - "exist"
            -> "correlation name" from an outer query can be used in a subquery in the "WHERE" clause.

        - "correlated subquery"
            -> A subquery that uses a correlation name from an outer query

        - "not exists"

    (3.8.4 Test for the Absence of Duplicate Tuples)
        - "unique"
            -> returns the value "true" if the argument subquery contains no duplicate tuples.

            * Almost no major db implements it. Mostly not used!!!

    (3.8.5 Subqueries in the From Clause)
        - SQL allows a subquery expression to be used in the "from" clause.
            ex)
                SELECT *
                FROM (SELECT ...)
                WHERE ...;

        * some SQL implementations, MYSQL and POSTGRESQL, require that each subquery relation in the "FROM" clause must be given a name.

        - "LATERAL"
            -> subquery can reference columns from tables that appear earlier in the FROM clause.

            ex)
                SELECT name, salary, avg_salary
                FROM instructor II, 
                LATERAL (SELECT avg(salary)
                         FROM instructor I2
                         WHERE I2.dept_name = I1.dept_name);

            * without the "LATERAL" clause, the subquery cannot access the correlation variable II from the outer query.

    (3.8.6 The With Clause)
        - "with"
            -> provides a way of defining a temporary relation whose definition is available only to the query in which the "WITH" clause occurs.

    (3.8.7 Scalar Subqueries)
        - SQL allows subqueries to occur wherever an expression returning a value is permitted, provided the subquery returns only one tuple containing a single attribute;

            ex)
                SELECT dept_name,
                    (SELECT COUNT(*)
                     FROM instructor
                     WHERE department.dept_name = instructor.dept_name)
                     AS num_instructors
                FROM department;

            * if the result has more than one tuple when the subquery is executed, the run-time error occurs.

    (3.8.8 Scalar Without a From Clause)
        - "DUAL" -> only used for ORACLE DB
